value.Title: Early Greek Philosophy
value.Description: The 6th and 5th centuries B.C.E. saw the beginnings of philosophy, science, medicine, and rhetoric in Greece.  This course will examine the major movements and texts in these areas, paying special attention to the growth of questions about the nature and possibility of human knowledge about the world, the divine, and human nature.  Our main texts will be those of the so-called Presocratics (including Xenophanes, the Pythagoreans, Heraclitus, Parmenides, and the later Eleatics, pluralists, and atomists) but we will also explore ancient medicine and rhetoric as well.  This upper-level undergraduate course will be a seminar, with discussion, frequent reading notes, a seminar report, and a substantial term paper expected from students.  Prerequisites: at least three philosophy courses, with at least two at the 300-level or above; or consent of the instructor.
